# Density
# It is the continuous and smoothed version of the histogram
# estimated from the data.
# To calculate this, divide the frequency of a group 
# by the width of it.

# density histogram

ggplot(data=tips, aes(x = tip)) + 
  geom_histogram(aes(y = ..density..),
                 colour = 1, fill = "white", binwidth=.5) +
  geom_density(size=1,col="blue")
## Warning: Using `size` aesthetic for lines was deprecated in ggplot2 3.4.0.
##  Please use `linewidth` instead.
## Warning: The dot-dot notation (`..density..`) was deprecated in ggplot2 3.4.0.
##  Please use `after_stat(density)` instead.

# Normal distribution

# X ~ Normal (mean=mu, variance=sigma^2)
# X ~ Normal (mean=mu=0, variance=sigma^2=1), Standard normal distribution


# Generate data from a normal distribution

# DePauw, N=1600

#rnorm(x, mean=mu, sd=sigma)
round(rnorm(10, mean=21, sd=1),1)
##  [1] 20.7 21.1 22.1 21.7 21.6 23.8 20.2 21.2 19.7 22.7
# Generate age of 1600 students

set.seed(43435)  # choose any numbers
age <- round(rnorm(1600, mean=21, sd=1),1)

# Draw a density histogram

df <- data.frame(age=round(rnorm(1600, mean=21, sd=1),1))
head(df)
##    age
## 1 21.4
## 2 21.0
## 3 22.6
## 4 20.8
## 5 21.0
## 6 20.2
ggplot(data=df, aes(x = age)) + 
  geom_histogram(aes(y = ..density..),
                 colour = 1, fill = "white", binwidth=.1) +
  geom_density(size=1,col="blue")

# Overlay a normal density curve
# dnorm(x, mean=mu, sd=sigma)

ggplot(data=df, aes(x = age)) + 
  geom_histogram(aes(y = ..density..),
                 colour = 1, fill = "white", binwidth=.75) +
  #geom_density(size=1,col="blue")+
  
  stat_function(fun=dnorm,
               args=list(mean=mean(df$age),
                         sd=sd(df$age)),
               col="red", size=1)

#Two Exercises_________________________________________
# Draw a Q-Q- plot

ggplot(data=df, aes(sample=age))+
  stat_qq(col="blue",size=3)+
  stat_qq_line(col="red",size=2)

# Sampling from a normally distributed population
# Show that if x~Normal(mean=mu,variance=sigma^2)
# then xbar ~ Normal (mean of xbar =mu, variance of xbar=sigma^2/n)

n=10  # sample size
m=5000    # simulation size
sample_means = c(NA,m)
for (i in 1:m)
{
  sample_means[i] <- mean(sample(df$age,n))
}
head(sample_means)
## [1] 21.42 21.37 20.65 20.61 20.93 20.97
# plotting a histgram of sample_means

df1 <- data.frame(sample_means=sample_means)
head(df1)
##   sample_means
## 1        21.42
## 2        21.37
## 3        20.65
## 4        20.61
## 5        20.93
## 6        20.97
ggplot(data=df1, aes(x = sample_means)) + 
  geom_histogram(aes(y = ..density..),
                 colour = 1, fill = "white", binwidth=.25) +
  #geom_density(size=1,col="blue")+
  
  stat_function(fun=dnorm,
                args=list(mean=mean(df1$sample_means),
                          sd=sd(df1$sample_means)),
                col="red", size=1)

# Draw a Q-Q- plot

ggplot(data=df1, aes(sample=sample_means))+
  stat_qq(col="blue",size=1)+
  stat_qq_line(col="red",size=2)

# Sample from a non-normal distribution
#-----------------------------------------
# If X has mean=mu and variance sigma^2, and if n>=30,
# by the Central Limit Theorem, 
# xbar apporimately follows normal with mean of xbar=mu
# and variance of xbar = sigma^2/n.



n=40  # sample size
m=5000    # simulation size
sample_means1 = c(NA,m)
for (i in 1:m)
{
  sample_means1[i] <- mean(sample(tips$tip,n))
}
head(sample_means1)
## [1] 3.01250 2.89050 3.41375 2.80500 2.87750 2.83800
# plotting a histgram of sample_means

df2 <- data.frame(sample_means1=sample_means1)
head(df2)
##   sample_means1
## 1       3.01250
## 2       2.89050
## 3       3.41375
## 4       2.80500
## 5       2.87750
## 6       2.83800
ggplot(data=df2, aes(x = sample_means1)) + 
  geom_histogram(aes(y = ..density..),
                 colour = 1, fill = "white", binwidth=.10) +
  #geom_density(size=1,col="blue")+
  
  stat_function(fun=dnorm,
                args=list(mean=mean(df2$sample_means1),
                          sd=sd(df2$sample_means1)),
                col="red", size=1)

ggplot(data=tips, aes(x = tip)) + 
  geom_histogram(aes(y = ..density..),
                 colour = 1, fill = "white", binwidth=.5) +
  geom_density(size=1,col="blue")+

stat_function(fun=dnorm,
              args=list(mean=mean(tips$tip),
                        sd=sd(tips$tip)),
              col="red", size=1)

# Draw a Q-Q- plot

ggplot(data=df2, aes(sample=sample_means1))+
  stat_qq(col="blue",size=1)+
  stat_qq_line(col="red",size=2)
